Below is your solution in Julia programming language.

```julia
using Statistics

function weather_data_analyzer(temps)
    if length(temps) == 0
        return (; average=nothing, max=nothing, min=nothing, trend=nothing)
    else
        stats = (average=mean(temps), max=maximum(temps), min=minimum(temps))
        diffs = diff([1, temps...])
        if all(x -> x > 0, diffs)
            return (; trend = :increasing, stats...)
        elseif all(x -> x < 0, diffs)
            return (; trend = :decreasing, stats...)
        else
            return (; trend = :stable, stats...)
        end
    end
end
```
This function first checks if the list of daily temperature data is empty. If it's empty, then it returns a named tuple with all values set to `nothing`. Otherwise, it calculates the average, max and min temperatures and determines the trend (increasing, decreasing or stable) by checking the differences in consecutive elements.
